I was a little confused too. 
Per my understanding, an `Router` in `Invalid` state is not actually **INVALID**. An actual **INVALID** `Router` is the one with `RLOC16 == 0xFFFF`. The implementation of `RouterTable::GetNextEntry` has confirmed it too: 
```cpp
const Router *RouterTable::GetNextEntry(const Router *aRouter) const
{
    VerifyOrExit(aRouter != NULL, OT_NOOP);
    aRouter++;
    VerifyOrExit(aRouter < &mRouters[Mle::kMaxRouters], aRouter = NULL);
    VerifyOrExit(aRouter->GetRloc16() != 0xffff, aRouter = NULL);

exit:
    return aRouter;
}
```

So, a `Router` of `Invalid` state would just mean that the `Router` is totally unreachable, but all those link information is still sound. Maybe these information can be useful later?

