This is *ok* but there are two models that I think improve this:

In the case where you want to stick to a well defined API:

```python
class ThingAPI(ABC):
    ...

class Thing(ThingAPI):
    @classmethod
    def make_thing(cls) -> ThingAPI:
        ...
```

This pattern helps enforce the defined API and is only the right solution in some cases.

In all of the other cases:

```python
T = TypeVar("T")

class Thing:
    @classmethod
    def make_thing(cls: Type[T]) -> T:
        ...
```

This ensures that in the case of subclassing, the return type isn't locked into the base class.

