@anntzer I think the way I've set things up a inheritance will be tricky as I understand it-

Here are the methods that are common:
   * `compute_likelihood`
   * `_generate_sample_from_state`
   * `_initialize_sufficient_statistics`
   * `_accumulate_sufficient_statistics`
   * ` _get_n_fit_scalars_per_param`
   * `_check_and_set_categorical_n_features` (already made free-standing)

Because of how inheritance is used, `_initialize_sufficient_statistics` and `_accumulate_sufficient_statistics`  would still need to call the parent method.  However, a `_BaseCategoricalHMM` would not derive from the necessary classes to still ensure that `super()._initialize_sufficient_statistics does the right thing.

I think we'd end up with something like this:
```mermaid
  graph TD;
      BaseEstimator-->BaseHMM
      BaseHMM-->VariationalBaseHMM;
      BaseHMM-->CategoricalHMM;
      VariationalBaseHMM-->VariationalCategoricalHMM;
      _BaseCategorial-HMM->CategoricalHMM;
      _BaseCategorial-HMM->VariationalCategoricalHMM;
```

So, I don't see a way to insert `_BaseCategoricalHMM` into the inheritance hierarchy and still make things work.  One option would be to at least make `_BaseCategoricalHMM`, with static methods, and have each of the Variational/EM classes call methods into it.  This would at least make the code centralized, and allow further evolution over time.

